This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring December 1, 2010, as Helsinki Human Rights Day. The proclamation commemorates the 35th anniversary of the Helsinki Final Act, which established the principles of lasting security and respect for human rights in Europe. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of security rooted in cooperation, transparency, and respect for human rights. It recognizes the courageous human rights activists who have worked to uphold these principles and calls on participating states to reexamine their compliance with their commitments. The proclamation concludes by urging the people of the United States to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.